-- allium: 3
-- specs/graphs/cuda_graph_reuse.allium
--
-- Scope: the CUDA backend's multi-entry cudaGraphExec cache and the
-- per-call reuse / patch / instantiate decision the backend takes on
-- every ggml_backend_cuda_graph_compute. The contracts here describe
-- the CACHE MECHANISM that the upstream (libllama) `can_reuse_graph`
-- bailout currently bypasses for `transformer_kv.n_stream > 1`.
-- This spec is INDEPENDENT of that bailout: it describes what the
-- backend offers when reuse IS attempted. Tier 2 work in
-- PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md drops the libllama bailout; the cache
-- behaviour described here must continue to hold.
--
-- Why this spec exists: the topology-hash-keyed cache + the
-- cudaGraphExecUpdate patch path is load-bearing for two future
-- phases:
--   1. Tier 2 extends per-stream view patching to the K/V *read*
--      views in llm_build_kqv. The patch surface relies on the
--      backend tolerating src_address changes for GGML_OP_VIEW /
--      GGML_OP_CPY nodes between calls. If the backend later
--      tightens that tolerance (e.g. to require src_address
--      equality), Tier 2 silently breaks.
--   2. Tier 3 unifies dispatch into one llama_decode per tick with
--      n_stream baked into ne[3]. The topology hash collapses the
--      per-stream variants into one cache entry; the dtype-strict
--      invariant prevents cross-dtype reuse that would otherwise
--      submit mismatched bytes to a kernel templated on the
--      captured dtype (the suspected mechanism behind the
--      multi-slot concat.cu:202 GGML_ASSERT crash).
--
-- The mechanism has been in tree since PHASE 36-38 and is stable;
-- this spec pins the load-bearing properties so subsequent
-- refactors do not silently regress them.
--
-- Includes:
--   - External entities for the runtime objects involved
--     (CudaContext, CgraphInput, CapturedGraph, ExecutableGraph,
--     GraphCacheEntry, NodeProperties).
--   - Enumerations for the cache-action a tick takes and the ggml
--     op kinds whose src_address mismatch is tolerated.
--   - Contracts for the load-bearing properties:
--     CUDAGraphCache (capacity + FIFO eviction),
--     TopologyHashLookup (key derivation + miss handling),
--     CudaGraphExecUpdate (patch-vs-reinstantiate semantics),
--     DtypeStrictness (no reuse across dtype change),
--     ViewCpyAddressTolerance (src_address ignored for VIEW/CPY).
--   - System-wide invariants binding the cache size bound, the
--     dtype invariant, the tolerance scope, and an
--     EventualEviction liveness property.
--   - Open questions for points the implementation leaves ambiguous
--     (FIFO vs LRU; what `cudaGraphExecUpdateFailure` means for the
--     next call).
--
-- Excludes:
--   - The libllama `can_reuse_graph` bailout itself
--     (src/llama.cpp:580-628). That decision lives one layer up and
--     concerns whether to submit the captured cgraph at all; this
--     spec governs the backend's behaviour given that the cgraph
--     IS submitted. The interaction is one-way: lifting the
--     bailout (Tier 2 work) does not change any contract here.
--   - The cuda_graph_probe instrumentation
--     (ggml-cuda.cu:4796-4824, 4878-4946). The probe records
--     telemetry that is zero-cost when GGML_CUDA_GRAPH_PROBE is
--     unset; no contract depends on its values.
--   - The disable_due_to_* fallbacks (gpu_arch < CC_TURING,
--     too_many_updates >= 4, failed_graph_capture). These are
--     escape hatches that bypass the cache entirely; they are
--     observable via ctx->cur_graph = nullptr but are not part
--     of the reuse-path invariants this spec asserts.
--   - The kv_size bucketing to multiples of 64
--     (src/llama.cpp:621). That is a libllama-side reuse policy
--     and lives in the same layer as `can_reuse_graph`.
--   - The K/V read-view stream patching gap that Tier 2 will close.
--     Owned by specs/kv-cache/per_stream_read_view_patching.allium
--     (forthcoming, P0.B.S1.b). THIS spec asserts only what the
--     backend already does; the patching mechanism that Tier 2
--     will exercise lives there.

-- ============================================================
-- External entities — CUDA backend cache objects
-- ============================================================

-- One ggml_backend_cuda_context. Owns the cuda_graphs map keyed by
-- topology hash (std::unordered_map<uint64_t,
-- std::unique_ptr<ggml_cuda_graph>>). Field declared in
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda/common.cuh:888.
entity CudaContext {
    device: Integer
    use_cuda_graph: Boolean
    cache_size: Integer                    -- mirrors ctx.cuda_graphs.size()
}

-- One ggml_cgraph submitted to ggml_backend_cuda_graph_compute. The
-- per-call shape and node sequence the backend must either
-- capture-fresh, patch, or reuse-as-is.
entity CgraphInput {
    n_nodes: Integer
    topology_hash: Integer                 -- ggml_cuda_graph_get_topology_key(cgraph)
    shape_hash: Integer                    -- ggml_cuda_graph_get_shape_key(cgraph)
}

-- One captured cudaGraph_t paired with its instantiated
-- cudaGraphExec_t and the per-node properties used to decide
-- whether the next call requires update. Mirrors struct
-- ggml_cuda_graph in ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda/graph.cuh:20-49.
entity GraphCacheEntry {
    topology_key: Integer                  -- cache map key
    shape_key: Integer                     -- last instantiated shape
    has_captured_graph: Boolean            -- ggml_cuda_graph.graph != nullptr
    has_executable: Boolean                -- ggml_cuda_graph.instance != nullptr
    number_consecutive_updates: Integer    -- self-disable counter
    hits_total: Integer                    -- probe-only telemetry
}

-- One per-node fingerprint stored on a GraphCacheEntry. Used by
-- ggml_graph_node_has_matching_properties to decide whether the
-- next call's matching node differs in a way that requires the
-- whole executable to be patched (cudaGraphExecUpdate) or fully
-- reinstantiated. Mirrors struct ggml_graph_node_properties in
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda/graph.cuh:9-18.
entity NodeProperties {
    entry: GraphCacheEntry
    node_index: Integer
    node_op: GgmlOp
    node_type: GgmlType                    -- dst tensor dtype
    node_address: Integer                  -- dst data pointer
    src_address_0: Integer                 -- per-src dst data pointer (GGML_MAX_SRC)
    src_type_0: GgmlType                   -- per-src dtype
}

-- One node in a submitted CgraphInput. Carries the current values
-- the backend compares against NodeProperties on the matching
-- GraphCacheEntry. Modelled as an external entity so the
-- invariants can quantify over both sides of the comparison.
entity CgraphNode {
    cgraph: CgraphInput
    node_index: Integer
    op: GgmlOp
    dst_type: GgmlType
    dst_address: Integer
    src_address_0: Integer
    src_type_0: GgmlType
}

-- ============================================================
-- Enumerations
-- ============================================================

-- The action the backend takes for one call against a cached
-- topology key. Determined by ggml_cuda_get_graph (lookup or
-- insert-with-eviction) and is_cuda_graph_update_required (decides
-- between reuse-as-is and patch/reinstantiate). The
-- `instantiate_then_reuse` action covers a miss: a fresh capture
-- followed by cudaGraphInstantiate then a normal launch.
enum CacheAction {
    reuse_unchanged                        -- topology + per-node fingerprints match; cudaGraphLaunch only
    exec_update                            -- topology matches; node fingerprints differ; cudaGraphExecUpdate patches
    reinstantiate                          -- exec_update returned cudaErrorGraphExecUpdateFailure; destroy + cudaGraphInstantiate
    instantiate_then_reuse                 -- topology key missed in cache; fresh capture + instantiate + launch
}

-- The ggml op kinds this spec quantifies over. Only the two
-- src_address-tolerant ops (VIEW, CPY) and a sentinel `other`
-- are needed; the contract makes no further per-op distinction.
enum GgmlOp {
    op_view                                -- GGML_OP_VIEW
    op_cpy                                 -- GGML_OP_CPY
    op_scale                               -- GGML_OP_SCALE (op_params comparison required)
    op_other                               -- every other ggml op kind
}

-- Distinct ggml tensor dtypes for the DtypeStrictness invariant.
-- The spec asserts properties of dtype CHANGE, so only the kinds
-- that appear in the production graph need named values. Production
-- runs Q4_0 K/V; F16/F32 are dominant on activations.
enum GgmlType {
    type_f32 | type_f16 | type_bf16 | type_q4_0 | type_q4_0_ar16 | type_other
}

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- The maximum number of cache entries the backend retains
    -- before FIFO eviction. Mirrors the default in
    -- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4539 (size_t 128) and the
    -- override env GGML_CUDA_GRAPH_MAX checked at line 4534.
    -- Implementations may set any value >= 1.
    max_cache_entries: Integer = 128

    -- The threshold at which the backend self-disables CUDA-graph
    -- use for a given topology entry. Mirrors the >= 4 check in
    -- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:5069. After this many
    -- consecutive `cuda_graph_update_required` decisions on the
    -- same entry, the backend falls back to direct node-by-node
    -- evaluation for that topology key. This is an escape hatch,
    -- not a contract surface; named here only so invariants can
    -- distinguish "live" entries from disabled ones.
    consecutive_update_disable_threshold: Integer = 4
}

-- ============================================================
-- Contracts
-- ============================================================

-- The CUDAGraphCache — the multi-entry cache itself. Lives in
-- ggml_backend_cuda_context.cuda_graphs
-- (ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda/common.cuh:888) with lookup +
-- insertion + eviction in ggml_cuda_get_graph at
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4549-4576. Capacity is set by
-- ggml_cuda_get_graph_cache_max at line 4532-4542.
contract CUDAGraphCache {
    invoke: (ctx: CudaContext) -> Set<GraphCacheEntry>

    @invariant CapacityBoundedByConfig
        -- The cache size never exceeds max_cache_entries. The
        -- bound is enforced at insertion in ggml_cuda_get_graph
        -- (ggml-cuda.cu:4557-4566): a while-loop evicts entries
        -- until size < cap before the new entry is inserted. The
        -- bound holds across the lifetime of the CudaContext;
        -- ctx.cache_size <= max_cache_entries at every observable
        -- point.

    @invariant FIFOEvictionUnderPressure
        -- When the cache is full and a new topology key misses,
        -- entries are dropped via ctx.cuda_graphs.erase(begin())
        -- (ggml-cuda.cu:4565). std::unordered_map iteration order
        -- is implementation-defined but stable enough that the
        -- first-inserted entry tends to be evicted first; the
        -- contract is "evict ONE entry" rather than a strict LRU
        -- ordering. Implementations MUST evict at least one entry
        -- when at capacity AND a new topology must be inserted.

    @invariant EntryFreesUnderlyingCudaResources
        -- Erasing a cache entry destroys the std::unique_ptr<
        -- ggml_cuda_graph>, which runs ~ggml_cuda_graph() and
        -- frees cudaGraphExec_t + cudaGraph_t. No leaked device
        -- memory or executable graph survives eviction. (The
        -- destructor is declared at ggml-cuda/graph.cuh:22 and
        -- defined in ggml-cuda.cu near the cuda_graphs anchor;
        -- the contract names the property the destructor must
        -- uphold.)

    @guidance
        -- The default cap of 128 is large enough that production
        -- workloads (single-layer reuse + MTP draft + n_kv
        -- bucketing) typically miss the bound. Eviction is
        -- observable only on workloads with many distinct
        -- topologies (multi-model, repeated context resizing,
        -- mixed prefill/decode where the bucketing window is
        -- under-tuned). The cap exists to make a pathological
        -- workload fail safely rather than out-of-memory the
        -- driver.
}

-- The TopologyHashLookup — the keying scheme. Lives at
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4509-4520
-- (ggml_cuda_graph_get_topology_key) with the lookup at
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4549-4576
-- (ggml_cuda_get_graph). The shape_key (ggml-cuda.cu:4487-4502)
-- is recorded as telemetry on the entry but is NOT the cache key;
-- the comment at line 4506-4508 records this design choice
-- explicitly.
contract TopologyHashLookup {
    invoke: (cache: Set<GraphCacheEntry>, cgraph: CgraphInput) -> GraphCacheEntry

    @invariant KeyDerivedFromOpSequenceOnly
        -- The topology_hash is FNV-1a 64-bit over (cgraph.n_nodes,
        -- per-node op). It deliberately does NOT mix in node->ne
        -- or src_address — those changes are absorbed by the
        -- CudaGraphExecUpdate path. Two CgraphInputs with the
        -- same op-sequence collide on topology_hash regardless
        -- of element-count or pointer-value differences.

    @invariant LookupHitReturnsExistingEntry
        -- If the cache contains an entry with topology_key =
        -- cgraph.topology_hash, the lookup returns that entry.
        -- No new entry is allocated; the entry's hits_total and
        -- last_use_us are updated in-place.

    @invariant LookupMissAllocatesNewEntry
        -- If no entry matches the topology_hash, the lookup
        -- allocates a fresh ggml_cuda_graph, inserts it under
        -- the topology_hash key, and returns it with
        -- has_captured_graph = false and has_executable = false.
        -- Eviction (per CUDAGraphCache.FIFOEvictionUnderPressure)
        -- happens before the insertion if at capacity.

    @invariant NoCrossTopologyAliasing
        -- A cache entry under topology_key K is consulted ONLY
        -- when the submitted cgraph's topology_hash = K. Reuse
        -- of an entry against a cgraph with a different
        -- topology_hash is not possible by construction: the
        -- map lookup either hits the right key or misses
        -- entirely.
}

-- The CudaGraphExecUpdate — the patch path for a topology hit
-- whose per-node fingerprints have drifted. Lives at
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4740-4781
-- (is_cuda_graph_update_required) and
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4783-4825
-- (update_cuda_graph_executable). The per-node comparison
-- mechanism is ggml_graph_node_has_matching_properties at
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4687-4738.
contract CudaGraphExecUpdate {
    invoke: (entry: GraphCacheEntry, cgraph: CgraphInput) -> CacheAction

    @invariant UpdateOnFingerprintDrift
        -- If the submitted cgraph has the same topology_hash as
        -- entry.topology_key BUT one or more nodes' properties
        -- (ne, nb, dst_address for non-VIEW/CPY ops, src_address
        -- for non-VIEW/CPY ops, dtypes, op_params for SCALE)
        -- differ from the entry's stored fingerprint, the
        -- backend calls cudaGraphExecUpdate(entry.instance,
        -- entry.graph) to patch the executable. The captured
        -- cgraph (entry.graph) is replaced by the new one
        -- BEFORE the update call (see capture-end at
        -- ggml-cuda.cu:4871-4886). The fingerprint vector
        -- entry.ggml_graph_properties is rewritten in place by
        -- set_ggml_graph_node_properties at
        -- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4672-4685.

    @invariant ReuseUnchangedWhenAllFingerprintsMatch
        -- If is_cuda_graph_update_required returns false
        -- (every node's properties match), no update or
        -- capture happens; cudaGraphLaunch on the existing
        -- entry.instance is the only device-side work. The
        -- entry.number_consecutive_updates counter is reset to
        -- 0 (ggml-cuda.cu:5065). This is the fast path Tier 2's
        -- per-stream view-patching enables for read-view
        -- changes (which today force a fingerprint mismatch
        -- because src_address differs).

    @invariant UpdateFailureFallsBackToReinstantiate
        -- If cudaGraphExecUpdate returns
        -- cudaErrorGraphExecUpdateFailure, the backend
        -- destroys entry.instance and calls cudaGraphInstantiate
        -- with the freshly captured graph (ggml-cuda.cu:
        -- 4812-4816). The cache entry persists; only the
        -- executable is replaced. This is the safety valve when
        -- the new fingerprint is structurally incompatible
        -- (e.g. nb stride change beyond what CUDA's update path
        -- accepts).

    @invariant ConsecutiveUpdatesSelfDisable
        -- If entry.number_consecutive_updates reaches
        -- consecutive_update_disable_threshold, the backend
        -- sets entry.disable_due_to_too_many_updates and
        -- bypasses the cache entirely for that topology on
        -- subsequent calls (ggml-cuda.cu:5069-5079). The entry
        -- remains in the map for hits_total accounting; new
        -- calls fall through to direct node-by-node compute.
        -- This is an escape hatch, not a contract surface; the
        -- spec names it so callers can reason about why a
        -- nominally-reusable topology stops reusing.

    @guidance
        -- The patch path is the load-bearing mechanism for
        -- Tier 2: extending per-stream patching to read views
        -- in llm_build_kqv produces a per-stream src_address
        -- change EVERY decode. Without exec_update, those
        -- changes would force a full reinstantiate per tick;
        -- the captured cudaGraph + cudaGraphExecUpdate avoids
        -- that. Tier 2 must verify that the read-view
        -- src_address change does not force
        -- cudaErrorGraphExecUpdateFailure (it should not,
        -- because the ne/nb shapes are unchanged); if it does,
        -- the consecutive-update self-disable will trigger
        -- after 4 ticks and the cache will silently fall back
        -- to direct evaluation.
}

-- The DtypeStrictness invariant as a contract surface. Lives at
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4698-4711 (the node->type
-- and src->type checks in ggml_graph_node_has_matching_properties).
-- The comment at line 4698-4702 records the load-bearing intent.
contract DtypeStrictness {
    invoke: (entry: GraphCacheEntry, node: CgraphNode) -> Boolean

    @invariant DstDtypeMismatchInvalidatesNode
        -- For any node, if node.dst_type differs from the
        -- corresponding NodeProperties.node_type stored on the
        -- matching entry, the node fails the matching check.
        -- This forces cuda_graph_update_required = true and the
        -- backend takes the exec_update path. cudaGraphExecUpdate
        -- WILL fail in this case (the captured graph's kernel was
        -- templated on the original dtype), and the
        -- reinstantiate path runs — submitting a fresh capture
        -- with the new dtype.

    @invariant SrcDtypeMismatchInvalidatesNode
        -- For any node, if any src[i].type differs from the
        -- corresponding NodeProperties.src_type[i] stored on the
        -- matching entry, the node fails the matching check.
        -- Same fallback path as DstDtypeMismatchInvalidatesNode.

    @invariant DtypeChangeIsNeverSilentlyReused
        -- The two clauses above together guarantee that no
        -- captured cudaGraphExec is reused with a node whose
        -- dtype changed between capture and re-submission. This
        -- is the property the spec exists to assert: a graph
        -- captured at F16 must not be reused with F32 inputs,
        -- because the kernel template selection bakes the
        -- dtype into the launch parameters. Violating this is
        -- the suspected mechanism behind the multi-slot
        -- concat.cu:202 GGML_ASSERT crash (see the comment at
        -- ggml-cuda.cu:4698-4702).

    @guidance
        -- DtypeStrictness is the structural reason the n_stream
        -- 4D port could land without re-exposing the
        -- concat.cu:202 crash: the layout change altered some
        -- tensor types in unrelated graph paths, and the
        -- dtype-strict node-match invalidates ALL prior cache
        -- entries on the first decode after the change. The
        -- cache rebuilds from scratch with the new dtypes; no
        -- stale entry survives.
}

-- The ViewCpyAddressTolerance — the asymmetric tolerance for
-- src_address (and dst_address) mismatch on GGML_OP_VIEW and
-- GGML_OP_CPY nodes only. Lives at
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4687-4731 (the two
-- early-return clauses in ggml_graph_node_has_matching_properties:
-- the dst-address check at lines 4688-4692 and the per-src loop
-- at lines 4722-4730).
contract ViewCpyAddressTolerance {
    invoke: (entry: GraphCacheEntry, node: CgraphNode) -> Boolean

    @invariant ViewCpySrcAddressMismatchToleratedOnVcpy
        -- For nodes where op = op_view OR op = op_cpy, a
        -- per-src src_address mismatch between node.src_address
        -- and NodeProperties.src_address on the matching entry
        -- does NOT invalidate the match. The per-call src
        -- pointer is updated via the cpy_dest_ptrs indirection
        -- (ggml-cuda.cu:4647 + 4665-4666) rather than baked into
        -- the captured kernel parameters.

    @invariant ViewCpyDstAddressMismatchToleratedOnVcpy
        -- For nodes where op = op_view OR op = op_cpy, a
        -- node.dst_address mismatch with
        -- NodeProperties.node_address does NOT invalidate the
        -- match (the dst-address early-return at
        -- ggml-cuda.cu:4688-4691 carves out exactly these two
        -- ops). The dst pointer follows the same indirection
        -- mechanism as src.

    @invariant AddressMismatchInvalidatesEveryOtherOp
        -- For any node with op = op_other (every ggml op kind
        -- other than VIEW and CPY), a src_address or dst_address
        -- mismatch DOES invalidate the match. The captured
        -- kernel for those ops has the pointer baked into its
        -- launch parameters; reusing it against a different
        -- pointer would write to the wrong device address.

    @invariant OpScaleParamsMustMatch
        -- For op = op_scale, the op_params (32 bytes,
        -- GGML_MAX_OP_PARAMS) must match between the entry
        -- fingerprint and the current cgraph node. SCALE bakes
        -- its scalar into op_params; a change there changes the
        -- computed result and must invalidate the match. Lives
        -- at ggml-cuda.cu:4732-4735. SCALE is named explicitly
        -- because its op_params carry a value the kernel reads;
        -- other ops' op_params are either compile-time fixed or
        -- absorbed into ne/nb (which the match check already
        -- compares).

    @guidance
        -- The asymmetric tolerance is what makes the per-stream
        -- view patching tractable: K/V write CPY operations
        -- (update_cache_copies in src/llama.cpp:630-720) update
        -- node->src[1]->data every decode without invalidating
        -- the cached executable. Tier 2 extends the same pattern
        -- to the K/V read views in llm_build_kqv, which are
        -- GGML_OP_VIEW nodes — already inside the tolerance
        -- carve-out. The mechanism is pre-supported; what Tier 2
        -- adds is the libllama-side patching code.
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants — system-wide
-- ============================================================

-- The capacity invariant lifted to the system level. For any
-- CudaContext at any observable moment, the cache holds at most
-- max_cache_entries entries. Eviction (per the
-- FIFOEvictionUnderPressure contract clause) maintains this
-- bound under workload pressure.
invariant CacheBounded {
    for ctx in CudaContexts:
        ctx.cache_size <= max_cache_entries
}

-- The dtype-strictness invariant lifted to the system level.
-- For any CgraphNode submitted in a tick that reuses a cached
-- entry without forcing reinstantiate, the dtype of every src
-- and the dst MUST match the captured fingerprint. Implementation
-- enforces this via the early-returns in
-- ggml_graph_node_has_matching_properties at
-- ggml-cuda.cu:4703-4711 (dst.type and src.type checks).
invariant NoReuseAcrossDtypeChange {
    for node in CgraphNodes:
        let entry = MatchingCacheEntryFor(node)
        let action = CacheActionFor(node)
        exists entry and action = reuse_unchanged
            implies (node.dst_type = NodePropertiesAt(entry, node.node_index).node_type
                     and node.src_type_0 = NodePropertiesAt(entry, node.node_index).src_type_0)
}

-- The tolerance scope lifted to the system level. For any
-- CgraphNode whose op is NOT VIEW or CPY (and not SCALE, which
-- has its own op_params constraint), src_address and dst_address
-- equality is a necessary condition for reuse_unchanged. The
-- invariant phrases the carve-out negatively: address mismatch
-- on a non-VIEW/CPY op DOES invalidate the match.
invariant AddressToleranceScopedToViewCpy {
    for node in CgraphNodes:
        let entry = MatchingCacheEntryFor(node)
        let props = NodePropertiesAt(entry, node.node_index)
        let action = CacheActionFor(node)
        (exists entry
         and action = reuse_unchanged
         and node.op != op_view
         and node.op != op_cpy)
            implies (node.dst_address = props.node_address
                     and node.src_address_0 = props.src_address_0)
}

-- The liveness companion to CacheBounded: under sustained
-- pressure from new topology keys, entries DO get evicted (the
-- cache does not deadlock at the cap). Formally: if the cache
-- is at capacity and a topology key is submitted that does not
-- match any existing entry, at least one entry will be removed
-- before the new entry is inserted. The implementation upholds
-- this via the while-loop at ggml-cuda.cu:4557-4566.
invariant EventualEviction {
    for ctx in CudaContexts:
        for cgraph in CgraphInputsAt(ctx):
            (ctx.cache_size = max_cache_entries
             and not TopologyKeyInCache(ctx, cgraph.topology_hash))
                implies SomeEntryEvictedBeforeInsert(ctx, cgraph)
}

-- The reuse-correctness composition: if the backend takes the
-- reuse_unchanged action on a node, every property the captured
-- kernel depends on matches. This is the implication of
-- ReuseUnchangedWhenAllFingerprintsMatch from the
-- CudaGraphExecUpdate contract, lifted to a system property over
-- every reused node.
invariant ReuseImpliesPropertyMatch {
    for node in CgraphNodes:
        let entry = MatchingCacheEntryFor(node)
        let props = NodePropertiesAt(entry, node.node_index)
        let action = CacheActionFor(node)
        action = reuse_unchanged
            implies (node.op = props.node_op
                     and node.dst_type = props.node_type
                     and node.src_type_0 = props.src_type_0)
}

-- ============================================================
-- Open Questions
-- ============================================================

-- OQ-1: FIFO vs LRU. The comment at ggml-cuda.cu:4528-4531 records
--   that eviction is FIFO-by-insertion-order "for simplicity" and
--   that std::unordered_map iteration order is
--   implementation-defined. If a workload emerges where the
--   evicted entry happens to be the hottest one (the bound-but-
--   stale entries survive while the next-tick re-use is dropped),
--   the choice may need to revisit. Today no such workload is on
--   record. The hits_total + last_use_us telemetry on each entry
--   (ggml-cuda.cu:4553-4554) supports a switch to LRU if needed;
--   no contract here precludes it.
--
-- OQ-2: cudaGraphExecUpdateFailure → reinstantiate-then-retry vs
--   reinstantiate-then-drop. The current code (ggml-cuda.cu:4812-
--   4821) destroys the entry.instance, calls cudaGraphInstantiate
--   with the new captured graph, and assumes success. There is no
--   retry on the update path itself. If a future workload sees
--   cudaErrorGraphExecUpdateFailure at a high rate (e.g. due to
--   structural drift the topology hash doesn't catch), the
--   cost of reinstantiate per tick may be material. The
--   consecutive-update self-disable at threshold=4 is the current
--   release valve; revisit if the threshold trips frequently in
--   production telemetry.
--
-- OQ-3: scope of the SCALE op_params clause. Other ops also carry
--   op_params (ROPE, NORM, ALIBI, etc.) but the matching check
--   only compares op_params for op = SCALE (ggml-cuda.cu:4732-
--   4735). If an op_params-bearing op other than SCALE starts
--   carrying values that the captured kernel reads at launch time
--   (rather than baking at JIT time), the check needs extending.
--   No such case is known today; the spec records the gap so a
--   future op landing with that property prompts a contract
--   update.
--
-- OQ-4: multi-context interaction. The cache is per
--   ggml_backend_cuda_context (one per CUDA device). Production
--   runs --device CUDA0,CUDA1 with one context per device; each
--   context has its own cuda_graphs map and the contracts above
--   hold independently per context. Cross-context coordination
--   (e.g. shared eviction policy under combined VRAM pressure) is
--   not modelled here; today the bound is per-context and the
--   aggregate worst case is N_devices * max_cache_entries.
--   Acceptable on the current 2-GPU geometry; revisit if a
--   future system runs 8+ GPUs per process.

